    "# Automated cell-to-cell matching: what we tried, why it hit a wall\n",
    "\n",
    "*A plain-English summary of 60+ experimental sessions.*\n",
    "\n",
    "## The problem in one paragraph\n",
    "\n",
    "We have two different microscope images of the same piece of mouse brain.\n",
    "One image (called **CZ**) has about 800 cells, each carefully picked by\n",
    "hand. The other image (called **HCR**) has 10,000 to 30,000 cells — the\n",
    "same brain tissue, but chemically expanded to roughly double its size,\n",
    "rotated 180°, and imaged differently. Our job is to figure out, for\n",
    "every CZ cell, which HCR cell is the *same physical cell*. Today this\n",
    "is done by hand; we are trying to automate it.\n",
    "\n",
    "The two images don't line up cleanly because:\n",
    "\n",
    "- the expansion isn't uniform (it stretches more in depth than sideways),\n",
    "- the cells themselves warp as the tissue expands,\n",
    "- only **a small fraction** of HCR cells have the green marker that\n",
    "  identifies candidates (roughly 3–10% of them),\n",
    "- so for each CZ cell, we're looking for one match in a haystack of\n",
    "  thousands of mostly-wrong neighbours.\n",
    "\n",
    "We measure success as **\"match rate within 20 µm\"** — the fraction of\n",
    "hand-labeled ground-truth cells that the algorithm places within a\n",
    "cell-diameter of the correct HCR cell."
   ]
  },
