    "## 1. How well can any single method do it?\n",
    "\n",
    "We built and tested more than a dozen different matching algorithms.\n",
    "Some use only the 3D positions of cells (point clouds). Some use the\n",
    "cell shapes (segmentation masks). Some use the raw image brightness.\n",
    "Some are learned by neural networks. The plot below shows the\n",
    "**three strongest single methods**, measured on each of six brain\n",
    "samples.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **P1** — a geometric outlier-tolerant matcher (TEASER).\n",
    "- **P4** — a graph-matching method using cell neighborhoods.\n",
    "- **P6** — a non-rigid, Bayesian-style warping method (BCPD).\n",
    "\n",
    "No single method wins across all samples. Different methods are best\n",
    "for different situations: P1 is strongest on clean, medium-density\n",
    "brains; P4 is strongest on dense brains; P6 sits in between."
   ]
